Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Postulate 6: The Antisymmetry Principle", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8080672523249693`*^9, 
  3.808067269919386*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6caf60f8-56af-434e-bd77-\
acc5970d9e42"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Statement of the Postulate", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8080672904992204`*^9, 
  3.8080672942113757`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bb9c3e08-0537-4907-acfa-\
3af7ecde9321"],

Cell["\<\
In any system containing a set of identical particles, there is no observable \
that gives information on which particle is being measured. Thus, any labels \
on particles are artificial, and when the coordinates of any two particles \
are exchanged, the absolute square of the wavefunction must not change. 

Therefore, the total wavefunction must be antisymmetric with respect to \
complete exchange of coordinates of any two fermions. Electronic spin must be \
included in these coordinates.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.8080673021538053`*^9, 3.808067363108737*^9}, {
  3.80806785555368*^9, 3.808067978308324*^9}, {3.808068010849341*^9, 
  3.808068103205638*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ae415f8e-2abf-430e-99e7-\
bcdb643ae713"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Antisymmetry Principle", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.808068128964388*^9, 
  3.808068133830553*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b625d6de-49e0-4e31-9081-\
ffac9389b6c7"],

Cell["\<\
The first part of this statement perhaps can be understood in the context of \
the previous postulates. The second part of the statement, which is the heart \
of the postulate, likely doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t make any sense yet. It\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s called the antisymmetry principle, and it has to do with \
what happens when we flip the coordinates of any two fermions in our \
wavefunction. Electrons are fermions, and we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll discuss this \
principle more when talking about multielectron atoms and molecules.\
